  13. SECURITY & CRYPTANALYSIS

  13.1 Algorithm Weaknesses

  Caesar Cipher:
  - Vulnerability: Only 25 possible keys
  - Attack: Brute force (try all 25 shifts)
  - Time: Seconds by hand, milliseconds by computer
  - Defense: None - fundamentally insecure

  Vigenère Cipher:
  - Vulnerability: Repeating key pattern
  - Attack Methods:
    a. Kasiski Examination: Find repeating ciphertext sequences
    b. Friedman Test: Calculate index of coincidence
    c. Frequency Analysis: Once key length known, treat as multiple Caesar ciphers
  - Defense: Use key as long as message (→ one-time pad)

  Playfair Cipher:
  - Vulnerability: Digraph frequency patterns
  - Attack: Analyze letter pair frequencies (THE → specific digraph)
  - Strength: 26² = 676 possible digraphs vs 26 letters
  - Defense: Much harder than Caesar/Vigenère but still breakable

  ---
  13.2 Implementation Security Notes

  This Implementation:
  - ✗ NOT cryptographically secure: Uses random not secrets
  - ✗ No authentication: Can't verify message integrity
  - ✗ No key derivation: Keys used as-is
  - ✗ Timing attacks: No constant-time operations
  - ✓ Educational only: Clearly documented as such

  Modern Cryptography Would Use:
  - AES-256 (symmetric encryption)
  - RSA (asymmetric encryption)
  - HMAC (message authentication)
  - PBKDF2/Argon2 (key derivation)
  - Constant-time comparisons

